<doc id="372620" wikidata="Q1778169" url="?curid=372620" title="Schur complement">
<text>The Schur complement is a key tool in the fields of linear algebra, the theory of matrices, numerical analysis, and statistics.

It is defined for a block matrix. Suppose &quot;p&quot;, &quot;q&quot; are nonnegative integers such that &quot;p + q &gt; 0&quot;, and suppose &quot;A&quot;, &quot;B&quot;, &quot;C&quot;, &quot;D&quot; are respectively &quot;p&quot; × &quot;p&quot;, &quot;p&quot; × &quot;q&quot;, &quot;q&quot; × &quot;p&quot;, and &quot;q&quot; × &quot;q&quot; matrices of complex numbers. Let
formula_1
so that &quot;M&quot; is a (&quot;p&quot; + &quot;q&quot;) × (&quot;p&quot; + &quot;q&quot;) matrix.

If &quot;D&quot; is invertible, then the Schur complement of the block &quot;D&quot; of the matrix &quot;M&quot; is the &quot;p&quot; × &quot;p&quot; matrix defined by
formula_2
If &quot;A&quot; is invertible, the Schur complement of the block &quot;A&quot; of the matrix &quot;M&quot; is the &quot;q&quot; × &quot;q&quot; matrix defined by
formula_3
In the case that &quot;A&quot; or &quot;D&quot; is singular, substituting a generalized inverse for the inverses on &quot;M/A&quot; and &quot;M/D&quot; yields the generalized Schur complement.

The Schur complement is named after Issai Schur who used it to prove Schur&#x27;s lemma, although it had been used previously. Emilie Virginia Haynsworth was the first to call it the &quot;Schur complement&quot;. The Schur complement is sometimes referred to as the &quot;Feshbach map&quot; after a physicist Herman Feshbach.

==Background==
The Schur complement arises when performing a block Gaussian elimination on the matrix &quot;M&quot;. In order to eliminate the elements below the block diagonal, one multiplies the matrix &quot;M&quot; by a &quot;block lower triangular&quot; matrix on the right as follows:
formula_4
where &quot;Ip&quot; denotes a &quot;p&quot;×&quot;p&quot; identity matrix. As a result, the Schur complement formula_5 appears in the upper-left &quot;p&quot;×&quot;p&quot; block.

Continuing the elimination process beyond this point (i.e., performing a block Gauss–Jordan elimination),
formula_6
leads to an LDU decomposition of &quot;M&quot;, which reads
formula_7
Thus, the inverse of &quot;M&quot; may be expressed involving &quot;D&quot;−1 and the inverse of Schur&#x27;s complement, assuming it exists, as
formula_8
The above relationship comes from the elimination operations that involve &quot;D&quot;−1 and &quot;M/D&quot;. An equivalent derivation can be done with the roles of &quot;A&quot; and &quot;D&quot; interchanged. By equating the expressions for &quot;M&quot;−1 obtained in these two different ways, one can establish the matrix inversion lemma, which relates the two Schur complements of &quot;M&quot;: &quot;M/D&quot; and &quot;M/A&quot; (see &quot;Derivation from LDU decomposition&quot; in ).

== Properties ==

* If &quot;p&quot; and &quot;q&quot; are both 1 (i.e., &quot;A&quot;, &quot;B&quot;, &quot;C&quot; and &quot;D&quot; are all scalars), we get the familiar formula for the inverse of a 2-by-2 matrix:
: formula_9
: provided that &quot;AD&quot; − &quot;BC&quot; is non-zero.
* In general, if &quot;A&quot; is invertible, then
: formula_10
: whenever this inverse exists.
* (Schur&#x27;s formula) When &quot;A&quot;, respectively &quot;D&quot;, is invertible, the determinant of &quot;M&quot; is also clearly seen to be given by
: formula_11, respectively
: formula_12,
: which generalizes the determinant formula for 2 × 2 matrices.
* (Guttman rank additivity formula) If &quot;D&quot; is invertible, then the rank of &quot;M&quot; is given by
: formula_13
* (Haynsworth inertia additivity formula) If &quot;A&quot; is invertible, then the &quot;inertia&quot; of the block matrix &quot;M&quot; is equal to the inertia of &quot;A&quot; plus the inertia of &quot;M&quot;/&quot;A&quot;.
* (Quotient identity) formula_14.
* The Schur complement of a Laplacian matrix is also a Laplacian matrix.

== Application to solving linear equations ==
The Schur complement arises naturally in solving a system of linear equations such as 

formula_15.

Assuming that the submatrix formula_16 is invertible, we can eliminate formula_17 from the equations, as follows.

formula_18

Substituting this expression into the second equation yields
: formula_19

We refer to this as the &quot;reduced equation&quot; obtained by eliminating formula_17 from the original equation. The matrix appearing in the reduced equation is called the Schur complement of the first block formula_16 in formula_22:
: formula_23.

Solving the reduced equation, we obtain
: formula_24

Substituting this into the first equation yields
: formula_25

We can express the above two equation as:
: formula_26

Therefore, a formulation for the inverse of a block matrix is:
: formula_27

In particular, we see that the Schur complement is the inverse of the formula_28 block entry of the inverse of formula_22.

In practice, one needs formula_16 to be well-conditioned in order for this algorithm to be numerically accurate.

This method is useful in electrical engineering to reduce the dimension of a network&#x27;s equations. It is especially useful when element(s) of the output vector are zero. For example, when formula_31 or formula_32 is zero, we can eliminate the associated rows of the coefficient matrix without any changes to the rest of the output vector. If formula_32 is null then the above equation for formula_17 reduces to formula_35, thus reducing the dimension of the coefficient matrix while leaving formula_31 unmodified. This is used to advantage in electrical engineering where it is referred to as node elimination or Kron reduction.

==Applications to probability theory and statistics==

Suppose the random column vectors &quot;X&quot;, &quot;Y&quot; live in R&quot;n&quot; and R&quot;m&quot; respectively, and the vector (&quot;X&quot;, &quot;Y&quot;) in R&quot;n&quot; + &quot;m&quot; has a multivariate normal distribution whose covariance is the symmetric positive-definite matrix

:formula_37

where formula_38 is the covariance matrix of &quot;X&quot;, formula_39 is the covariance matrix of &quot;Y&quot; and formula_40 is the covariance matrix between &quot;X&quot; and &quot;Y&quot;.

Then the conditional covariance of &quot;X&quot; given &quot;Y&quot; is the Schur complement of &quot;C&quot; in formula_41:

:formula_42

If we take the matrix formula_43 above to be, not a covariance of a random vector, but a &quot;sample&quot; covariance, then it may have a Wishart distribution. In that case, the Schur complement of &quot;C&quot; in formula_43 also has a Wishart distribution.

== Conditions for positive definiteness and semi-definiteness ==

Let &quot;X&quot; be a symmetric matrix of real numbers given by
formula_45
Then
* If &quot;A&quot; is invertible, then &quot;X&quot; is positive definite if and only if &quot;A&quot; and its complement &quot;X/A&quot; are both positive definite:
:formula_46
* If &quot;C&quot; is invertible, then &quot;X&quot; is positive definite if and only if &quot;C&quot; and its complement &quot;X/C&quot; are both positive definite:
:formula_47
* If &quot;A&quot; is positive definite, then &quot;X&quot; is positive semi-definite if and only if the complement &quot;X/A&quot; is positive semi-definite:
:formula_48
* If &quot;C&quot; is positive definite, then &quot;X&quot; is positive semi-definite if and only if the complement &quot;X/C&quot; is positive semi-definite: 
:formula_49

The first and third statements can be derived by considering the minimizer of the quantity
formula_50
as a function of &quot;v&quot; (for fixed &quot;u&quot;).

Furthermore, since
formula_51
and similarly for positive semi-definite matrices, the second (respectively fourth) statement is immediate from the first (resp. third) statement.

There is also a sufficient and necessary condition for the positive semi-definiteness of &quot;X&quot; in terms of a generalized Schur complement. Precisely,
* formula_52 and
* formula_53

where formula_54 denotes a generalized inverse of formula_16.

